project: zenmetrics — CPU full-mode wall for the 6 perceptual metrics (task #141)
date: 2026-05-29
host: lilith (AMD Ryzen 9 7950X 16-Core, 32 threads, 128 GB RAM, water-cooled)
os: Linux 6.6.114.1-microsoft-standard-WSL2

purpose:
  Clean CPU wall-time per (metric, mode, size) for the CPU-vs-GPU crossover
  table (task #141). Joined with the already-committed GPU cold one-shot
  (benchmarks/gpu_coldstart_2026-05-29.tsv) and GPU warm per-call
  (benchmarks/gpu_metrics_sweep_2026-05-28.tsv) to produce
  benchmarks/cpu_gpu_crossover_2026-05-29.tsv + docs/CPU_GPU_CROSSOVER_2026-05-29.md.

harness: benchmarks/heaptrack/drivers/cpu_profile/src/bin/cpu_wall.rs  (binary: cpu-wall)
  zenbench 0.1.8 interleaved round-robin (NOT criterion) — kills thermal/turbo
  bias via randomized per-round ordering + paired statistics + loop-overhead
  compensation. One zenbench group per size; all metric/mode cells interleave
  under identical machine conditions. Score sentinels (record_scores) confirm
  each cell ran the REAL full-mode score, not a stub.

  Task #141 added the "4096" (4096^2 = 16 MP) size label so the CPU wall join
  lands on the SAME sizes as gpu_coldstart_2026-05-29.tsv (512/1024/2048/4096),
  and added a CPU_WALL_NO_GATE=1 env toggle that swaps zenbench's resource gate
  for GateConfig::disabled(). RATIONALE: the default gate does a full sysinfo
  process enumeration every round, per cell, to detect concurrent benchmark
  harnesses + system noise. On this box (~1000 live processes, many idle claude
  sessions) that per-round scan dominated wall time — the metric thread sat in
  hrtimer_nanosleep while the scan ran, so measurement crawled (observed: 2 s CPU
  in 23 s wall for dssim@512). Disabling the gate restored full-speed measurement
  (dssim@512: 31 s -> 4 s wall, CPU == wall). The interleaved round-robin +
  paired stats that make zenbench better than criterion are unaffected; only the
  auto-pause is dropped. The CALLER guaranteed a quiet machine (verified loadavg
  ~0.18 before each run, no fresh .workongoing markers, no heavy jobs).

build: cargo build --release --bin cpu-wall   (RUSTFLAGS="", NO -C target-cpu=native)
  Runtime archmage SIMD dispatch only — what users actually get. Global ~/.cargo
  only sets +simd128 scoped to [target.wasm32-wasip1] (irrelevant on x86_64).
toolchain: rustc 1.95.0 (59807616e 2026-04-14)

source_commit (workspace parent at measurement time): d91db20376b4
  (docs(gpu): cold-start findings doc + CHANGELOG, task #140). Rebased onto
  master@origin before push — CPU wall numbers do not depend on the jobctl crate.

dependency_versions (Cargo.lock):
  zenbench 0.1.8 · cvvdp 0.1.0 (path) · iwssim 0.1.0 (path) · zensim 0.3.0 (path)
  · fast-ssim2 0.8.1 · dssim-core 3.4.0 · butteraugli 0.9.4

inputs: deterministic synth (ref/dist) pair, identical pattern to the heaptrack
  cpu_profile driver. ref = procedural RGB; dist = ref with per-channel offsets
  (-8/-4/+12). Same shape at every size so wall scales only with pixel count.

sizes:
  512   = 512x512   (0.262 MP)   <- exact GPU-cold join
  1024  = 1024x1024 (1.049 MP)   <- exact GPU-cold join
  2K    = 2048x2048 (4.194 MP)   <- exact GPU-cold join (gpu cold "4mp")
  4096  = 4096x4096 (16.777 MP)  <- exact GPU-cold join (gpu cold "16mp")
  12MP  = 4000x3000 (12.0 MP)    <- CPU-only; GPU-cold NOT measured here
  30MP  = 6000x5000 (30.0 MP)    <- CPU-only; GPU-cold NOT measured here

modes per metric:
  full           — new()/build + one cold score (THE crossover input column)
  strip          — strip-walker cold (cvvdp/ssim2/butter/iwssim/zensim; dssim N/A)
  warm_ref/cold  — build+warm ref+1 score per iter
  warm_ref/warm  — ref warmed once outside loop, time only the per-call score
  warm_ref_strip/{cold,warm} — same, strip-bounded dist
  dssim has no strip walker (dssim-core 3.4) — only full + warm_ref rows.

run_layout:
  512 / 1024 / 2K : all 6 metrics in ONE interleaved group per size.
  4096 / 12MP / 30MP : per-metric (one group per metric) to bound peak RAM at
    30 MP, where holding 6 metrics' warmed references simultaneously would be
    heavy. Cells still interleave WITHIN each metric's modes (full vs strip vs
    warm — the comparison that matters).

NO EXTRAPOLATION: every cell is a real zenbench run at the stated dims.

columns: size_label  metric  mode  cold_or_warm  w  h  mean_ns  mean_ms  n_rounds  score
  mean_ms = the wall median (zenbench mean per call, loop-overhead-compensated).
  score   = full/strip score sentinel (proves a real computation ran).

cvvdp methodology note: this file's cvvdp wall is the ZENBENCH measurement (same
  methodology as the other 5 metrics). It deliberately differs from
  crates/cvvdp/benchmarks/cpu_path_a_recovered_2026-05-29.tsv, which timed a
  SINGLE score() call per run (median of 7, cpu-profile driver t_score_ms). At
  small sizes the single-call wall bakes in per-call fixed overhead that zenbench
  amortizes; the two converge above ~4 MP. The crossover table uses the zenbench
  cvvdp column for an internally consistent join and shows both numbers for
  transparency (docs/CPU_GPU_CROSSOVER_2026-05-29.md "cvvdp methodology note").
